<div class="body"><p> Labour's Jim McMahon won the seat with 17,322 votes, with a majority of 10,835 over his nearest rival John Bickley, the UK Independence Party candidate. </p><p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Newly-elected Labour MP Jim McMahonand Jeremy Corbyn embrace after the Oldham West and Royton by-election" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/83811629_jeremy-co_3517759b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Newly-elected Labour MP Jim McMahonand Jeremy Corbyn embrace after the Oldham West and Royton by-election</span><span class="credit">  Photo: PA</span></span></span></span></p><p> The seat had been held for decades by the late Labour MP Michael Meacher, most recently with a majority of 14,738 at May’s general election. </p><p> There were widespread reports of questionable activity at the by-election. One council worker told LBC radio: “I saw things outside polling stations that would make your hair curl. </p><p> “There were people outside the polling stations who simply didn't know what they were doing there.” </p><p> One Conservative councillor oversaw the counting of one box of postal votes and found 29 were for Labour, six for Ukip, three for the Tories and one for the Liberal Democrats. </p><p> The Telegraph understands that complaints were filed with the police alleging electoral fraud at the general election in May and May last year’s European and local elections. </p><p> Nigel Farage, the Ukip leader, said that he had “evidence from an impeccable source that today's postal voting was bent”. Some 7,400 out of 27,700 votes cast were postal ballots. </p><p>
<link href="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/embed.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/></p><p>
</p><div class="tgs__wrapper" id="tg-ms-2485"><object class="tgs__image" data="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/2485-14492208181441987510.svg" type="image/svg+xml"></object></div><script>(function(window,namespace,id){function Queue(){var q=[];return{'destroy':function(){q.length=0;q=null;},'push':function(cb){q.push(cb);},'start':function(){var l=q.length;var i=-1;while(++i!==l){q[i]();}q.length=0;}};}function noop(){}function loadScript(url,onComplete){var script=document.createElement('script');script.async=true;script.src=url;script.type='text/javascript';script.onload=function(){this.onload=null;this.onreadystatechange=null;onComplete();};script.onreadystatechange=function(){if(this.readyState!=='complete'){return;}this.onload=null;this.onreadystatechange=null;onComplete();};document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0].appendChild(script);}function ready(){loadScript('http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/'+id+'.js',noop);}window[namespace]=window[namespace]||{};var q=null;if(window[namespace].Switcher===undefined){if(window[namespace].SwitcherQueue===undefined){window[namespace].SwitcherQueue=q=new Queue();loadScript('http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/Switcher.min.js',function(){q.start();q.destroy();window[namespace].SwitcherQueue=q=null;delete window[namespace].SwitcherQueue;});}else{q=window[namespace].SwitcherQueue;}q.push(ready);}else{ready();}})(this,'Telegraphics','2485');</script><p></p><p> In one case, he said, a ballot box for one council ward containing “several hundred votes” was “99 per cent Labour”. He said: “We are collecting statements now and we will do that at a considered pace.” </p><p> He added: “Postal voting not only warps elections but leaves people open basically to intimidation. </p><p> “It is registered who is getting a postal vote. The postman delivers the vote at 10.30 and at 10.35 there is a knock on the door ‘we have come to collect your postal vote, can we help fill it in?’” </p><p> Mr Farage said: “serious questions need to be asked” about the “perverse” election result this morning. </p><p> A Ukip spokesman said: “When we have reviewed the evidence and if we believe it to be sufficiently strong we will go to the police, not to journalists, as is the right and proper thing to do.” </p><p> Complaints were filed with police by the Conservatives and Ukip in Oldham over allegations of electoral fraud at the general election in May this year and last year’s European and local elections. </p><p>
