</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1155" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1155" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T11:55:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>11:55</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Ukip consider police complaint over voter irregularities</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Ukip are considering taking their concerns about postal voter irregularities to the police, a spokesman has said. </p>
<p> People were seen carrying their postal votes into Oldham Central Mosque, although the mosque has since said that it does not permit political activity on its site. </p>
<p> <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/parliamentary-constituencies/oldham-west-and-royton/12032551/Nigel-Farage-says-Labours-Oldham-victory-bent.html" target="_blank">Nigel Farage, Ukip's leader, described the by-election result as "bent".</a> </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/Oldham-8_3517637b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"></span></span></span></p>
<p> One council worker told LBC: "I saw things outside polling stations that would make your hair curl. </p>
<p> "There were people outside the polling stations who simply didn't know what they were doing there." </p>
<p> However, Greater Manchester Police have confirmed that they have yet to receive any complaints about the by-election. </p>
<p> </p>
<iframe allowfullscreen="true" allowtransparency="true" class="twitter-tweet twitter-tweet-rendered" data-tweet-id="672735998607011840" frameborder="0" id="twitter-widget-2" scrolling="no" style="position: static; visibility: visible; display: block; width: 500px; height: 208.4px; padding: 0px; border: medium none; max-width: 100%; min-width: 220px; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;" title="Twitter Tweet"></iframe>
<script async="" charset="utf-8" src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script>
<p></p>
<p> Carolyn Wilkins, Acting Returning Officer, said: "Oldham Council has not received any formal complaints about allegations of postal voting irregularities in the Oldham West and Royton by election. </p>
<p> "This was the first election held in the country under Individual Electoral Registration (IER) and we had a high level of daily scrutiny and interest from all parties in our work. </p>
<p> "They will have seen that we have a robust system in place for adjudicating postal votes which includes comparing the signatures and dates of birth in the submitted postal vote application to those within the postal vote statements. </p>
<p> "Where those do not match, the postal vote is rejected and not included in the count. </p>
<p> "We take our duties in administering the voting and count process very seriously and if we receive any allegations of postal voting irregularities then we would be immediately reported these to the police so they can be fully investigated." </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1150" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1150" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T11:50:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>11:50</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">If Corbyn replicated Oldham nationwide, he could be handed the keys to Downing Street</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> What would happen if the swing towards Labour seen in the seat of Oldham West this week was replicated across the nation in 2020? </p>
<p> Of course, the usual disclaimers apply; by-election results are very poor predictors of general elections, because every constituency is different; this is, as swingometer maestro Peter Snow would put it, "just a bit of fun". </p>
<p> But Labour is on a much better footing, potentially gaining 86 seats and being just eight seats short of a majority. </p>
<p>
<link href="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/embed.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/></p>
<div class="tgs__wrapper" id="tg-ms-2486"><object class="tgs__image" data="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/2486-14492294091444840019.svg" type="image/svg+xml"></object></div>
