</p><div id="update-20151204-1125" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1125" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T11:25:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>11:25</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Labour's new MP attacks George Osborne's Northern Powerhouse</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Jim McMahon, Labour's newly-elected MP, had this to say at the photocall this morning: </p>
<p> <i><span class="ssImg left"><img alt="Quote" height="40" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/01817/quotes_1817837a.gif" version="" width="45"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:45px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"></span></span></span> This is a truly overwhelming thing. For a local lad to represent the town he loves in Westminster is a big, big issue. I’m very clear; I am sick to death of what the Tories are doing to towns like Oldham. </i> </p>
<p> <i>"The whole Northern Powerhouse rhetoric is nothing more than a write-off of the north to create a poorhouse, and I’m sick of it. I think it’s about time that we show the Tories the people have had enough."</i> </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Newly-elected Labour MP Jim McMahonand Jeremy Corbyn embrace after the Oldham West and Royton by-election" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/83811629_jeremy-co_3517759b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Newly-elected Labour MP Jim McMahonand Jeremy Corbyn embrace after the Oldham West and Royton by-election</span><span class="credit">  Photo: PA</span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1118" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1118" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T11:18:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>11:18</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">No complaint over voter fraud</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Oldham's Returning Officer has yet to receive any complaints of voter fraud despite Nigel Farage accusing the process of being "bent". </p>
<p> The Electoral Commission says that suspicions should be reported to the Returning Officer and proof handed over to the police, neither of which it is believed Ukip has done so far. </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1105" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1105" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T11:05:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>11:05</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Ukip 'scarper off' from Oldham</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> <i>Laura Hughes, our political correspondent, reports from Oldham </i> </p>
<p> Ukip seem to have already packed up shop. Local shopkeeper says I've just missed them "scarper off." </p>
<p> This is their local office: shutters down, "to let" sign up. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Ukip's offices in Oldham" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/ukip-oldham-hq_3517773b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Ukip's offices in Oldham</span><span class="credit">  Photo: LAURA HUGHES</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> It didn't take them long to depart. This was Nigel Farage outside the office a little earlier: </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Nigel Farage at Ukip's offices in Oldham" height="319" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/nigel-farage-ukip-_3517785b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Nigel Farage at Ukip's offices in Oldham</span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1100" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1100" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T11:00:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>11:00</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Ukip's Suzanne Evans: 'We're bad losers'</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Ukip's deputy chairman Suzanne Evans says the party risks "sounding like bad losers" after Nigel Farage criticised the by-election result as "bent". </p>
<p> She told fellow Ukippers that "the voters have spoken" and that even without any irregularities in postal voting the "harsh reality" is that the party would still have lost. </p>
<p> In a Facebook post she warned: "So the voters have spoken and they’ve stuck with the status quo in Oldham. I must admit to being surprised at the result. We had an excellent candidate in John Bickley and the political wind was in our favour: an unprecedented migrant crisis; the Tories in disarray over tax credits; and the Labour party leadership in meltdown. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03297/Suzanne-evans_3297123b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Suzanne Evans, Ukip's deputy chairman</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> "As Nigel said on BBC Breakfast earlier, this result shows Labour is still ahead of us in the North of England, but UKIP is the only alternative and we must rise to the challenge of continuing to broadening our appeal and showing we’re a party for all Britons. </p>
<p> "As far as the postal vote issue is concerned, the harsh reality is that even without block postal voting we would still have lost in Oldham. But we made our manifesto commitment to scrapping the current postal voting system for good reason. It’s clearly open to widespread abuse. </p>
<p> </p>
<iframe allowfullscreen="true" allowtransparency="true" class="twitter-tweet twitter-tweet-rendered" data-tweet-id="672584699987017729" frameborder="0" id="twitter-widget-3" scrolling="no" style="position: static; visibility: visible; display: block; width: 500px; height: 186px; padding: 0px; border: medium none; max-width: 100%; min-width: 220px; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;" title="Twitter Tweet"></iframe>
<script async="" charset="utf-8" src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script>
<p></p>
<p> "But, there are far more non-voters in Oldham than there are postal voters. These are the people we must reach, those who are indifferent to or alienated from politics; those who don’t trust or who don’t see the relevance of our politicians. We’ve made huge gains here already, as we have with appealing more to women voters, so let’s keep going on this track; finish the job; and focus on what we can do to win next time, rather than risk just sounding like bad losers." </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1054" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1054" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T10:54:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>10:54</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Labour's victory celebrations</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Mr Corbyn arrived at Chadderton Town Hall to cheers from Labour supporters. </p>
<p> He congratulated Mr McMahon, who described his win as "overwhelming". </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/83811876_jeremy-co_3517757b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="credit">  Photo: PA</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> Mr Corbyn said the victory showed just how strong the party is. </p>
<p> He said: "It shows just how strong, how deep-rooted and how broad our party, the Labour Party, is for the whole of Britain." </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Newly-elected Labour MP Jim McMahonand Jeremy Corbyn share a hug after the Oldham West and Royton by-election" height="674" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/83811630_jeremy-co_3517758b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Newly-elected Labour MP Jim McMahonand Jeremy Corbyn share a hug after the Oldham West and Royton by-election</span><span class="credit">  Photo: PA</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> A small crowd held "vote Labour" placards as Mr Corbyn spoke and they cheered as cars driving past sounded their horns in support. </p>
<p> Mr Corbyn then quickly left the scene in a car without taking questions from journalists. </p>
<p> </p>
