<p></p>
<p> A Ukip spokesperson told The Telegraph: "When we have reviewed the evidence and if we believe it to be sufficiently strong we will go to the police, not to journalists, as is the right and proper thing to do." </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1035" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1035" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T10:35:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>10:35</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Jeremy Corbyn's victory speech in Oldham</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Jeremy Corbyn MP has arrived in Oldham to celebrate Jim McMahon’s by-election victory. He said: </p>
<p> “Labour victory in Oldham West and Royton is a ringing endorsement for Jim McMahon and the campaign we have been running since September against this Government’s cuts to Tax Credits and policing - and its damaging austerity policies. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Jeremy Corbyn with new Oldham West and Royton MP Jeremy Corbyn" height="326" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/corbyn-victory3_3517738b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Jeremy Corbyn with new Oldham West and Royton MP Jeremy Corbyn</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> “On a wet Thursday in December, the people of Oldham West and Royton have turned out in their thousands and voted for a Labour Party that is offering a real choice: between the politics of the few peddled by David Cameron and George Osborne - and the better, fairer Britain Labour stands for. </p>
<p> “The people of Oldham chose Labour values and Labour’s vision for the future. By increasing our share of the vote since the General Election, voters in Oldham have demonstrated that Labour is the real party of working people. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Jeremy Corbyn with new Oldham West and Royton MP Jeremy Corbyn" height="323" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/corbyn-victory2_3517739b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Jeremy Corbyn with new Oldham West and Royton MP Jeremy Corbyn</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> “We will now take our winning arguments to every constituency in the country - to convince the electorate, as we have in Oldham, that only Labour can deliver the economic and social justice our country is crying out for.” </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1023" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1023" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T10:23:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>10:23</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Tom Watson denies he wants to oust Jeremy Corbyn as leader amid fresh call for unity</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Despite Labour's victory last night, niggling questions about Jeremy Corbyn's leadership remain, albeit his future looks a lot more secure than it did 24 hours ago. </p>
<p> Deputy leader Tom Watson, asked by Radio 4 whether he wanted the top job, he said: "I never, ever, ever want to be leader of the Labour Party. I am very, very happy as deputy. I am enjoying my friendship and comradeship with Jeremy. We sometimes disagree with each other but that's politics. I am his deputy leader and I will defend him to the last." </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Tom Watson calls them 'awesome', but who are Drenge?" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/02608/tom-watson-2_2608964b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Tom Watson</span><span class="credit">  Photo: Jay Williams for the Telegraph</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> Mr Watson played down suggestions that the Momentum group was seeking to intimidate MPs who were critical of Mr Corbyn. </p>
<p> "They look like a bit of a rabble to me, but I don't think they are a problem for the Labour Party," he said. "I don't think they are effective. I think they are a bit of an irrelevance in the debate." </p>
<p> Responding to Ken Livingstone's suggestion that he would back moves to deselect MPs who voted for war, Mr Watson said: "I'm not entirely sure his words are helping the Labour Party. As the nearest we have to a Labour elder - he is getting on a bit, Ken - he should probably know that this is the week when we should be trying to bring people back together, but he is entitled to his opinions." </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Ken Livingstone" height="388" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/02122/KENLIVINGSTONE_2122535b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Ken Livingstone, Labour's former Mayor of London</span><span class="credit">  Photo: PA</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> Mr Watson denied that the former London mayor was running Mr Corbyn's office, insisting he had never seen him there. </p>
<p> He said the party needed a code of conduct on social media to prevent the kinds of abuses some MPs have complained of at the time of the Syria vote. </p>
<p> "To use an issue of such importance to try to divide the Labour Party is reprehensible," said Mr Watson. "I have seen those TV images of what went on in (Walthamstow MP) Stella Creasy's constituency and I can only say if there were Labour Party members on that demonstration, intimidating staff members of an MP like that, then I think they should be removed from the party. </p>
<p> "It's simply unacceptable that people conduct themselves in that way." </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-0934" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-0934" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T09:34:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>09:34</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Ukip cancels press conference</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Ukip had been encouraging the media to join it at a post-by-election press conference at 10am. </p>
<p> But it seems the party has now cancelled the meeting "due to a timings clash with Labour's press conference". </p>
<p> With Nigel Farage being accused of "sour grapes" this morning, it is also quite telling that the party's Oldham office won't pick up the phone to Laura Hughes, our political correspondent who is in the town. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Nigel Farage has said it would be “ridiculous” to deny him the opportunity to take part in the televised leaders’ debates" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/02872/nigel_2872052b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Nigel Farage has been accused of 'sour grapes'</span><span class="credit">  Photo: GETTY IMAGES</span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-0926" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-0926" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T09:26:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>09:26</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">George Osborne congratulates Jeremy Corbyn... as they share the same train to Manchester</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> This morning Jeremy Corbyn will be basking in the glory of Labour's win in Oldham West and Royton. </p>
<p> The Labour leader is heading up north to be with his new MP Jim McMahon. </p>
<p> But who should happen to be on the same time - none other than the Chancellor, George Osborne! </p>
