</p><div id="update-20151204-2305" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-2305" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T23:05:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>23:05</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Labour: "We have been playing down expectations"</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Labour are expected to hold onto Oldham with a reduced majority this evening, writes Laura Hughes in Oldham. </p>
<p></p>
<p> <i><span class="ssImg left"><img alt="Quote" height="40" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/01817/quotes_1817837a.gif" version="" width="45"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:45px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"></span></span></span> Labour sources in Oldham are estimating the voter turn out today is around 35 per cent, which will mean a substantially smaller majority for the party if they secure the seat. </i> </p>
<p> <i>This is the first test for Jeremy Corbyn since he was elected leader and one Labour source has suggested to me that Labour were more confident of winning than they were letting on publicly. </i> </p>
<p> <i>The idea was to play down expectations so more MPs and activists made the trip to Oldham and displayed loyalty to their leader. </i> </p>
<p> <i>I don't believe a single Conservative Cabinet member has made the trip up to Oldham during the campaign. </i> </p>
<p> <i>Cameron ordered every cabinet member to visit the other Oldham seat for the by election in 2010, but by the look of @olsconservative feed, no cabinet member or minister has made the trip. </i> </p>
<p> <i>Perhaps a new Tory tactic in the North? </i> </p>
<p></p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-2248" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-2248" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T22:48:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>22:48</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Labour expected to 'hang on'</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> The seat has been held for almost fifty years and insiders say the party is expecting to hold on to the seat - but may see their majority slashed. </p>
<p> Conversely Ukip, which beat the Conservatives to win 21% of the vote at the general election, is expecting to make some major inroads with this result. </p>
<p> It is the first electoral test for Jeremy Corbyrn since he won the Labour leadership, and Mr Farage claims his policies and leadership style has already alienated large numbers of Oldham voters. </p>
<p> Mr Corbyn posted this image on Twitter with just minutes to spare before the poll closed, which shows him hard at work canvassing voters. </p>
