</p><div id="update-20151204-1532" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1532" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T15:32:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>15:32</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Jeremy Corbyn's first electoral test</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn faces his first electoral test this evening when the results of the Oldham by-election are announced. </p>
<p> Polls close at 10pm - but can his party win the seat they have held for almost 50 years? And if they do win, how big will their majority be? </p>
<p> If Labour does badly it will add pressure on Mr Corbyn to resign as leader. Have a read at our analysis of <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/parliamentary-constituencies/oldham-west-and-royton/12031040/oldham-west-royton-by-election-results.html#update-20151203-1215">what a bad performance would mean for the party nationwide</a>. </p>
<p> Here's our very own cartoonist <strong>Christian Adams</strong>' take on events: </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Adams Cartoon, December 3" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03517/ADAMS031215_3517059b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Adams Cartoon, December 3</span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1511" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1511" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T15:11:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>15:11</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">The mood in Oldham this afternoon</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> <i>Laura Hughes, our Political Correspondent, is out and about in Oldham</i> </p>
<p> I've been walking around Oldham City centre for an hour now and have only managed to spot Ukip volunteers. </p>
<p> From what I've seen they seem to getting a fair amount of people's time, but it will be a question of whether or not the people of Oldham are willing to bare the winds and rain to actually come out and vote. </p>
<p> David Coburn, Ukip's MEP in Scotland, just told me: "I think Labour are just focusing on their core vote because that's all they've got. </p>
<p> "But even their core vote is extremely wobbly." </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Ukip's David Coburn" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03260/david-coburn-ukip_3260796b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">David Coburn, Ukip MEP</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> He said hard working people in Oldham feel "let down" by Labour and there's no doubting the fact Ukip will dent their majority here in this safe seat. </p>
<p> "I think Corbyn is a joke", he added. </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1406" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1406" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T14:06:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>14:06</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Campaign takes to the streets</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> This picture is just in from our political correspondent Laura Hughes who is in Oldham this afternoon. </p>
<p> It seems that Ukip are campaigning on the streets in order to secure more votes this afternoon. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="A Ukip campaigner in the Oldham West and Royton by-election" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03516/ukip-oldham-campai_3516994b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">A Ukip campaigner in the Oldham West and Royton by-election</span><span class="credit">  Photo: LAURA HUGHES</span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1230" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1230" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T12:30:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>12:30</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Even if it holds Oldham, Jeremy Corbyn's Labour has no answer to the Ukip squeeze</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> <i>Tom Harris argues that Nigel Farage does not pose the same danger to Labour as Nicola Sturgeon, but it may only be a matter of time</i> </p>
<p> Whichever party emerges as the victor in this week’s Oldham by-election, we know that the top two places will be occupied by Labour, the current incumbent, and Ukip. </p>
<p> That’s quite a remarkable observation when you consider that Nigel Farage’s party is barely 20 years old. The role of anti-establishment party in British by-elections is traditionally given to the Lib Dems and their predecessors, the Liberal Party, with its campaigning tradition stretching back not decades, but centuries. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Nigel Farage congratulates his party's candidate, John Bickley, (left) as he takes second place in the Wythenshawe and Sale East by-election " height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/02821/UKIP_BY_ELECTION__2821970b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Nigel Farage congratulates his party's candidate, John Bickley, (left) as he takes second place in the Wythenshawe and Sale East by-election </span><span class="credit">  Photo: Jon Parker Lee</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> But Ukip is the new insurgent. </p>
<p> <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12025058/What-would-it-mean-for-Labour-to-lose-the-Oldham-West-and-Royton-by-election.html" target="_blank">Whether it can snatch the late Michael Meacher’s seat from Labour or not</a>, Ukip has already transformed party politics in the 21st century. It holds the largest number of seats of any UK party in the European Parliament, has 500 council seats and, while taking a meagre single seat in this year’s general election, chalked up nearly four million votes, knocking the Lib Dems into a humiliating fourth place in share of the vote. </p>
<p> But is Nigel Farage’s claim this week – <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ukip/12029975/Nigel-Farage-Ukip-will-wipe-out-Labour-in-the-north-just-as-the-SNP-did-in-Scotland.html" target="_blank">that Ukip is about to do to Labour what the SNP has already done to it in Scotland</a> – mere boasting? Or are there genuine grounds for Labour to start preparing to cede more of those green benches to the purple people? </p>
<p> <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12030828/Even-if-it-holds-Oldham-Jeremy-Corbyns-Labour-has-no-answer-to-the-Ukip-squeeze.html" target="_blank">Continue reading Tom Harris's analysis.</a> </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1225" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1225" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T12:25:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>12:25</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Who are the candidates?</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> <iframe class="tg-card" data-id="d8b2980d-3b51-43c8-8a55-95a6e5d03cb6" frameborder="0" height="259" id="player2" scrolling="no" src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/breakoutCards/d8b2980d-3b51-43c8-8a55-95a6e5d03cb6.html" style="float: left; margin: 0px 0px 10px; height: 867px;" width="540"></iframe><script src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/assets/_scripts/embed-card.js"></script> </p>
<p> <iframe class="tg-card" data-id="60146c43-8cd9-45d3-a035-5dc90bb0f747" frameborder="0" height="259" id="player3" scrolling="no" src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/breakoutCards/60146c43-8cd9-45d3-a035-5dc90bb0f747.html" style="float: left; margin: 0px 0px 10px; height: 806px;" width="540"></iframe><script src="http://cf.eip.telegraph.co.uk/assets/_scripts/embed-card.js"></script> </p>
<p> The other candidates are: Liberal Democrats Jane Brophy, Conservative Party James Daly, Green Party Simeon Hart and Sir Oink A-Lot The Official Monster Raving Loony Party. </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1215" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1215" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T12:15:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>12:15</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">What would it mean if Labour lost?</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> <i>Asa Bennett and Laurence Dodds analyse recent polling and what it could mean if Labour lost </i> </p>
<p> Jeremy Corbyn faces his first electoral test since becoming leader as voters go to the polls for the <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/nigel-farage/12022787/Nigel-Farage-urges-Tory-voters-to-lend-him-their-vote-to-defeat-Labour-at-Oldham-by-election.html" target="_blank">Oldham West and Royton</a> by-election triggered by the death of much-loved Labour MP Michael Meacher. </p>
<p> Meacher won the seat in May with 14,000 more votes than Ukip's candidate – a majority which should be unassailable. But as Corbyn faces week after week of negative headlines, Labour insiders fear it could be dramatically slashed. </p>
<p> A private party poll last week <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12009844/Labour-support-at-ballot-box-could-be-halved-at-Oldham-by-election-polling-suggests.html" target="_blank">suggested it could drop by half</a>, while shadow chancellor John McDonnell this week seemed to be preparing <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12023806/Ukip-is-an-evil-force-John-McDonnell-says-as-Oldham-West-by-election-race-tightens.html" target="_blank">for a majority of less than 1,000</a>. </p>
<p> If that happened – of if, somehow, they lost the seat entirely – disgruntled Labour MPs who have so far stayed their hands might begin seriously thinking about a coup. </p>
<p> So how bad could it get? </p>
<p>
<link href="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/embed.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/></p>
<div class="tgs__wrapper" id="tg-ms-2471"><object class="tgs__image" data="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/2471-144905464277503665.svg" type="image/svg+xml"></object></div>
<script>(function(window,namespace,id){function Queue(){var q=[];return{'destroy':function(){q.length=0;q=null;},'push':function(cb){q.push(cb);},'start':function(){var l=q.length;var i=-1;while(++i!==l){q[i]();}q.length=0;}};}function noop(){}function loadScript(url,onComplete){var script=document.createElement('script');script.async=true;script.src=url;script.type='text/javascript';script.onload=function(){this.onload=null;this.onreadystatechange=null;onComplete();};script.onreadystatechange=function(){if(this.readyState!=='complete'){return;}this.onload=null;this.onreadystatechange=null;onComplete();};document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0].appendChild(script);}function ready(){loadScript('http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/'+id+'.js',noop);}window[namespace]=window[namespace]||{};var q=null;if(window[namespace].Switcher===undefined){if(window[namespace].SwitcherQueue===undefined){window[namespace].SwitcherQueue=q=new Queue();loadScript('http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/Switcher.min.js',function(){q.start();q.destroy();window[namespace].SwitcherQueue=q=null;delete window[namespace].SwitcherQueue;});}else{q=window[namespace].SwitcherQueue;}q.push(ready);}else{ready();}})(this,'Telegraphics','2471');</script>
<p></p>
<p> First, a health warning. By-election results can offer signs of trouble ahead, but they are famously poor predictors of general election results. This is partly because the composition of the electorate is different, and partly because their special, one-off nature makes voters do unusual things. </p>
<p> So as any pollster worth her salt will tell you, you can't just take a by-election result and generalise it across the entire country. </p>
<p> However, given the Labour party leadership is <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/12024146/Voters-support-bombing-Isil-in-Syria-much-more-than-Labour-would-have-you-think.html" target="_blank">currently touting online polls comprising a couple thousand of their supporters</a> as evidence of public opinion, we thought: why not do it anyway? </p>
<p> We consulted the political forecasting firm Electoral Calculus to generate some fantasy Oldham results, and then used their handy <a href="http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/userpoll.html" target="_blank">custom swing generator</a> to sketch out what would happen if these results were replicated on the national scale. </p>
<p> For instance, here's the implied result if Labour lost 25 per cent of its majority to Ukip. </p>
<p>
<link href="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/embed.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/></p>
<div class="tgs__wrapper" id="tg-ms-2474"><object class="tgs__image" data="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/2474-1449055008155430990.svg" type="image/svg+xml"></object></div>
