<p></p>
<p> If the last graph was Waterloo, this is War of the Worlds. Sure, Nigel Farage doesn't actually get to stomp around in a three-legged robot harvesting people's blood. But he does become the leader of Her Majesty's Opposition, consigning Labour to a minor role on par with the SNP. </p>
<p> Again, it's obviously unlikely that every single voter who deserted Labour instead fled to Ukip. But if we split the vote loss between Ukip and the Conservatives, things actually get worse for the Left: </p>
<p>
<link href="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/assets/embed.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"/></p>
<div class="tgs__wrapper" id="tg-ms-2475"><object class="tgs__image" data="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/MobileSwitcher/v2/images/2475-14490551152127486403.svg" type="image/svg+xml"></object></div>
