<p></p>
<p> Total Tory domination. But hey, at least Labour are bigger than Ukip – even though Ukip have received twice as many votes (an argument for PR?). </p>
<p> Like we said earlier, none of this will actually happen. We're having, as Peter Snow would say when playing with his swingometer, "<a href="https://www.ipsos-mori.com/newsevents/blogs/thepoliticswire/977/Predicting-2015-just-a-bit-of-fun.aspx" target="_blank">just a bit of fun</a>". The real picture will be much more complicated and probably somewhat milder. </p>
<p> But it does make clear just how big an earthquake it would be for Labour to lose votes in Oldham, let alone for them to lose the seat entirely. Even a much smaller tremor than any considered here would signal serious trouble ahead. </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1207" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1207" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T12:07:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>12:07</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Voters go to the polls</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Voters are heading to the polls today in the first by-election of this Parliament. </p>
<p> Constituents in Oldham West and Royton are casting their ballots in the tightly fought election which has seen recent polls in which Ukip is closing in on Labour who have comfortably held the seat for almost 50 years. </p>
<p> Ukip leader Nigel Farage was in the town this week to lend his support to candidate John Bickley in their campaign to cause a major by-election shock. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Nigel Farage congratulates his party's candidate, John Bickley, (left) as he takes second place in the Wythenshawe and Sale East by-election " height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/02821/UKIP_BY_ELECTION__2821970b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Nigel Farage congratulates his party's candidate, John Bickley, (left) as he takes second place in the Wythenshawe and Sale East by-election </span><span class="credit">  Photo: Jon Parker Lee</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> It will be left-winger Jeremy Corbyn's first electoral test since becoming the Labour leader. </p>
<p> The by-election comes following the death of long-serving Labour ex-minister Michael Meacher and has proved to be a hotly contested seat. </p>
<p> Although Labour has a majority of more than 14,000 in Oldham West and Royton, the odds have been tumbling on a win for Ukip. </p>
<p> <iframe frameborder="0" height="863" id="telegraphics-ccard-E14000871" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" scrolling="no" src="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/html/Years/2015/February/ConstituencyCards/oldham_west_and_royton.html?open=true&amp;title=false" style="height: 863px;" width="100%"> </iframe><script src="http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/SourceFiles/PostmessagerPat.min.js" type="text/javascript"> </script><script type="text/javascript">!function(e,t,n){function i(e){return function(){var n=t.getElementById('telegraphics-ccard-'+e),i=new PostmessagerPat,a='*';n.src+='',n.onload=function(){this.onload=null;var e={type:'origin'};i.publish(n.contentWindow,a,JSON.stringify(e))},i.subscribe(a,function(t){var i=null;try{i=JSON.parse(t.data)}catch(a){return}if(i.hasOwnProperty('id'))if(i.id===e)if('windowSize'===i.type)n.height=i.windowHeight,n.style.height=i.windowHeight+'px'})}}var a='_postmessenger';if(e[n])if(e[n].ConstituencyCards)return;e[n]=e[n]||{},e[n].ConstituencyCards={create:function(r){if(!e.PostmessengerPat){if(!e[n][a]){e[n][a]=[];var s=t.getElementsByTagName('head')[0]||t.documentElement,o=!1,c=t.createElement('script');c.type='text/javascript',c.src='http://s.telegraph.co.uk/graphics/SourceFiles/PostmessagerPat.min.js',c.onload=c.onreadystatechange=function(){if(!o)if(!this.readyState||'loaded'===this.readyState||'complete'===this.readyState){for(o=!0;e[n][a].length;)e[n][a].shift()();if(e[n][a]=null,delete e[n][a],c.onload=c.onreadystatechange=null,s)if(c.parentNode)s.removeChild(c),c=null,s=null}},s.insertBefore(c,s.firstChild)}e[n][a].push(i(r))}else i(r)()}}}(window,document,'Telegraphics'),Telegraphics.ConstituencyCards.create('E14000871');</script></p>
<p> The party came second in the constituency in the last general election with 21 per cent. </p>
<p> Mr Bickley will stand for the third time as a Ukip Westminster candidate and will go head-to-head with Labour's Jim McMahon. </p>
<p> Last October Mr Bickley nearly overturned an 11,000 Labour majority at the Heywood and Middleton by-election, losing by just 600 votes. </p>
<p> The other candidates are: Liberal Democrats Jane Brophy, Conservative Party James Daly, Green Party Simeon Hart and Sir Oink A-Lot The Official Monster Raving Loony Party. </p>
</div>
</div><p></p><p>
</p><div id="update-20151204-1200" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/BlogPosting">
<h3 class="was-h6"> <a href="#update-20151204-1200" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.url"> <time datetime="2015-12-04T12:00:00+00:00" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.datePublished"></time> <span>12:00</span> </a> </h3>
<h3 class="was-h3" itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.headline">Michael Meacher's death sparked by-election</h3>
<div itemprop="liveBlogUpdate.articleBody">
<p> Today's Oldham West and Royton by-election was sparked by the death of veteran Labour MP Michael Meacher in October who held the seat with a 15,000-strong majority. </p>
<p> Meacher, who died aged 75, was a long-serving MP who shrugged off a reputation as a pernickety Left-winger to become a useful member of Tony Blair’s government. </p>
<p> Branded “<a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10697120/Anthony-Neil-Wedgwood-Benn-obituary.html">Tony Benn</a>’s vicar on earth” by Neil Kinnock at the height of Labour’s internal strife, he managed for six years as environment minister to avoid most banana skins , before reverting to type as a critic of Blair’s policies. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg left"><img alt="Michael Meacher in 2007" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03478/2669593_Labour_Lea_3478879b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Michael Meacher in 2007</span><span class="credit">  Photo: Justin Sutcliffe</span></span></span></span></p>
<p> In office he reinforced New Labour’s green credentials. He handled his portfolio shrewdly, save for the embarrassment of a “fridge mountain” after officials misjudged an EU directive on the disposal of appliances containing greenhouse gases. </p>
<p> When the controversy over “Frankenstein food” GM crops erupted in 1999, it was the Cabinet Office minister Jack Cunningham, in charge of “selling” the idea, who caught the flak. Meacher staked out a more wary position without breaking with government policy that trials of such crops were desirable. </p>
<p> While Meacher’s superior, John Prescott, Labour’s deputy prime minister, fell out with many ministers who served under him, there was little friction between him and Meacher. Prescott was not particularly interested in the environment, and the two co-existed – except when Prescott tried to elbow Meacher out of leading Britain’s delegation to a summit in Johannesburg, giving way when environmental groups protested. </p>
<p></p>
<p> <span class="ssImg left"><img alt="Michael Meacher in 1999 during his tenure as Environment Minister " height="515" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03478/667759_0430_ENVIRO_3478882e.jpg" version="e" width="300"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:300px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Michael Meacher in 1999 during his tenure as Environment Minister </span></span></span></span></p>
<p></p>
<p> The parsonical Meacher had incurred ridicule, and £80,000 in costs, in 1988 when he sued <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/politics-obituaries/7702097/Alan-Watkins.html">Alan Watkins</a> of the Observer for asserting that he had falsely claimed working-class origins. Watkins’s counsel claimed that the public school-educated Meacher depicted himself as a farm labourer’s son when his father was an accountant who had retired to the family holding. </p>
<p> Meacher in court described his origins as “modest”, but earlier he had said: “I am very conscious of my privileged background. My strongest motivation in politics is guilt.” After 12 days the jury agreed with Watkins. </p>
<p> Later acquiring a second home in the Cotswolds, Meacher angered neighbours by seeking to fell 20 trees to create a tennis court, then in 1999 earned an instant slap-down from Blair for saying second-home ownership might have to be curbed. Meacher’s comment cost him the chance to head a new Department of Rural Affairs – a job given two years later to Margaret Beckett. </p>
<p> Meacher left the government in 2003 to campaign against genetically modified foods and the global power of the United States, urging the Cabinet to “rise up” against Blair. When in 2007 Blair stood down, Meacher prepared to run against Gordon Brown, but stepped aside for John McDonnell – who had more support among Labour MPs (and is now shadow chancellor), but not enough to mount a challenge. </p>
<p></p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Michael Meacher along with Pendle MP Gordon Prentice lead out local ramblers onto Boulsworth Moor, West Yorkshire in 1997" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03478/1681224_Freedom_to_3478885b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Michael Meacher along with Pendle MP Gordon Prentice lead out local ramblers onto Boulsworth Moor, West Yorkshire in 1997</span><span class="credit">  Photo: Howard Barlow</span></span></span></span></p>
<p></p>
<p> Meacher’s gaffes and dalliances with the hard Left led some to write him off. They overlooked his pedigree as a junior minister under Harold Wilson and James Callaghan, his relatively sure handling of six portfolios over 14 years in the shadow cabinet, and his ability to get on with people. </p>
<p> Originally an academic, during the Thatcher years Meacher gained a reputation for tying Tory ministers in statistical knots. Nigel Lawson christened him “the thinking man's Des Wilson", a tag not complimentary to the garrulous leader of Shelter. </p>
<p> In office, he showed application and attention to detail. This was not always appreciated: as a junior trade minister in the 1970s he had upset officials by redrafting parliamentary answers to give them a Eurosceptic flavour. Meacher’s secretary of state, <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1341502/Lord-Shore-of-Stepney.html">Peter Shore</a>, who shared his views on Europe, burned the midnight oil toning them down again. </p>
<p> Having entered politics a party moderate, by the time he worked with Shore he had established himself as a “Bennite”, having cut his ministerial teeth as one of Tony Benn’s lieutenants at the department of industry, promoting – to Harold Wilson’s alarm – greater public ownership and workers’ control. His allegiance to Benn remained strong and the two men co-sponsored a policy paper, Labour and Industry – the Next Steps (1975), which upset Wilson even more. Prior to the 1979 election, Meacher became founding chairman of the Labour Co-Ordinating Committee, an initially Bennite group campaigning for reflation, an end to private education and the transfer of the media to workers’ co-operatives. </p>
<p> Back in opposition Meacher joined Benn on the back benches, supporting his campaign to make Labour MPs “accountable” to local activists. When Callaghan resigned before the Left could push through its demand for the leader to be chosen by an electoral college, Meacher demanded that Labour MPs show activists their completed ballot papers. He sponsored Benn’s 1981 challenge to Denis Healey for the deputy leadership; during a dirty campaign which ended in Benn’s hair’s-breadth defeat, Meacher was never accused of foul play. </p>
<p> Meacher upset the leadership by urging that future Labour ministers be supplied with back-bench “progress-chasers” to hold them to their pledges; with Benn he opposed the sending of the Falklands task force, and he challenged the centrist Eric Varley for the party treasurership. </p>
<p> When Michael Foot resigned after the disastrous 1983 election, Meacher, with Benn’s machine behind him (Benn having lost his seat), went for the deputy leadership. At the height of a contest he had a chance of winning, Neil Kinnock destroyed his chances by telling Jilly Cooper: “People regard him as Benn’s vicar on earth. In reality he is kind, scholarly, innocuous … and weak as hell.” Roy Hattersley trounced Meacher by 67.2 per cent to 27.8. But he was elected to Labour’s national executive (NEC) and the Shadow Cabinet. </p>
<p> Meacher realised that the Bennite tide was ebbing and Labour’s only hope rested in unity under Kinnock. He backed the 1984-85 miners’ strike, but Arthur Scargill branded him a traitor for disowning violent pickets. He distanced himself further from the hard Left in voting to discipline Liverpool council’s Trotskyist deputy leader Derek Hatton, though not to expel him. He dropped out of Labour’s factional and leadership calculations when Robin Cook ousted him from the NEC in 1988 after his courtroom defeat . </p>
<p> Meacher’s Bennite period came to be viewed by some colleagues as an aberration or even a necessity for survival. Others were less forgiving and would have been unsurprised by his decision to throw his weight behind Jeremy Corbyn in the recent Labour leadership contest. </p>
<p> <span class="ssImg "><img alt="Meacher with Jeremy Corbyn in 2006" height="387" src="http://i.telegraph.co.uk/multimedia/archive/03478/449120_DTEM-Eddie__3478883b.jpg" version="b" width="620"/><span class="artImageExtras" style="max-width:620px;"><span class="ingCaptionCredit"><span class="caption">Meacher with Jeremy Corbyn in 2006</span><span class="credit">  Photo: Eddie Mulholland </span></span></span></span></p>
<p> Michael Hugh Meacher was born in Hemel Hempstead on November 4 1939, the son of George Meacher, a third-generation tenant farmer briefly articled to an accountant, and Doris Foxell, whose family owned a grocers shop. He won a scholarship to Berkhamsted School and went on to New College Oxford, taking a First in Greats. His mother wanted him to enter the Church, and he never abandoned his faith. </p>
<p> Meacher became secretary to the Danilo Dolci Trust, then a research fellow at the University of Essex; in 1966 he contested Colchester. He lectured in Social Administration at the University of York, and from 1970 at LSE. </p>
<p> By then Meacher had lost a safe seat at a by-election. Defending a 7,572 majority at Oldham West, he should have been home and dry, but June 1968 was the Wilson government’s low point and the Conservatives took the seat. Meacher won it back in 1970, and would hold it for 45 years. </p>
<p> The three-day week ordered by Heath during the 1973-74 miners’ strike put Meacher on the political map. Armed with statistics, he floored Heath in the House by asserting that the economic damage would cost £3 billion more than giving in to the miners’ pay claim. Livid, Heath ordered a “maul Meacher” initiative; this assured him of a job when, weeks later, Labour found itself unexpectedly back in office. </p>
<p> After a year with Benn at the Department of Industry, an exasperated Wilson moved Benn to Energy and Meacher to Social Services under Barbara Castle. </p>
<p> He arrived at his new department in difficult circumstances. His expertise related to tackling poverty, yet Britain was experiencing rampant inflation with unions grabbing what they could and the poor being left behind. He personally donated £500 to research the causes of low pay, but had barely settled at the DHSS when Callaghan succeeded Wilson and sacked Mrs Castle, moving Meacher to Trade. </p>
<p> After Labour’s defeat in 1979 he became a visiting professor at Surrey University and a valued member of the Treasury Select Committee. In 1980 Meacher launched a campaign over deaths in police custody using the home secretary Willie Whitelaw’s disclosure of 274 such deaths in a decade to demand a public inquiry. His campaigning over unexplained injuries to James Kelly, found dead in a Merseyside police cell, led the Police Federation to accuse him of “unsubstantiated smears”. </p>
<p> As social services spokesman from 1983, his call to Labour members of health authorities to monitor colleagues’ voting records provoked the former MP Eric Moonman to quit the party, accusing Meacher of “Stalinism” – and triggered the Observer article that prompted his self-destructive libel suit. </p>
<p> Tory MPs voiced outrage at Meacher’s claim that Margaret Thatcher was telling the elderly to “drop dead” at Christmas. They calculated his spending pledges prior to the 1987 election at £7 billion, and exploited an attack by him on American “colonialism” just as Kinnock was trying to bury the defence issue. </p>
<p> Meacher nevertheless fought a good campaign, and was rewarded with the Employment brief . Kinnock in 1989 moved him back to Social Services, where he percipiently denounced plans for a Child Support Agency as “half-baked”. Succeeding Kinnock in 1992, John Smith moved Meacher to Overseas Development, where he highlighted the plight of refugees as war flared in former Yugoslavia and embarrassed ministers over the “arms to Iraq” scandal. But after opposing Smith’s drive to curb union block voting at party conferences he was shunted sideways to be spokesman on John Major’s Citizen’s Charter. </p>
<p> After Smith’s death in 1994, Meacher returned to the mainstream as shadow transport minister. Before he could extract full capital from the birth pangs of the privatised railways, Blair demoted him to employment spokesman under David Blunkett, then to spokesman on environmental protection. </p>
<p> <iframe allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="304" id="player4" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/hYhUQhctTvY?enablejsapi=1" width="540"></iframe></p>
<p> During the Coalition, Meacher conducted a sustained campaign against the outsourcing of Work Capability Assessments on disabled people to the company Atos. In 2013 he so annoyed David Cameron that the prime minister accused him of taking “mind-altering substances”. </p>
<p> After the 2015 election, he was one of four MPs left from the intake of 1970, with Sir Gerald Kaufman – who became Father of the House – Dennis Skinner and Kenneth Clarke. </p>
<p> Michael Meacher married first, in 1962, Molly Reid (now Baroness Meacher); they had two sons and two daughters. The marriage was dissolved in 1987, and in 1988 he married, secondly, Lucianne Sawyer; she survives him with the children of the first marriage. </p>
<p> <strong>Michael Meacher, born November 4 1939, died October 21 2015 </strong> </p>
</div>
</div><p></p></div>

